 Plan: Fix remaining compile errors + cleanup

 Status

 Most implementation is DONE. These are the remaining fixes needed before the build compiles.

 Context

 The Android app was hardcoded to RFC1918 (192.168.1.100:8000) — unreachable outside the LAN.
 Finders will be worldwide. The winning key is worth ~$100K USD; we cannot rely on a manual
 submission button (attack vector, user error). Instead: automatic detection → encrypted
 transmission → immediate DGX sweep, with celebration UI and Aaron's contact number displayed.

 Architecture

 [Phone anywhere] → HTTPS → [Cloudflare edge] → tunnel → [DGX:8000 / api_server.py]
                    auto-POST on key found ↑              ↓ sweep TX (high fee, immediate)
                    retry loop (persist key locally)      ↓
                                                          [Finder's Bitcoin address]

 Cloudflare Tunnel: outbound-only TLS, no port-forwarding. Quick-start (trycloudflare.com temp
 URL) and production (named tunnel + custom domain) both documented in setup script.

 API key (X-API-Key header) protects all endpoints.

 Security principles

 - Found key never exposed to user — auto-POST only; key stored encrypted in SharedPrefs
 as backup retry cache; never shown on screen
 - On-device wallet — each phone generates its own Bitcoin keypair; private key stays on
 device forever; only the public address is registered with DGX for payout
 - Front-running defence — DGX verifies key cryptographically then broadcasts sweep TX
 with high fee priority (RBF, sat/vB >> current mempool) within seconds of receipt
 - Deduplication — DGX accepts first valid submission for each puzzle; subsequent identical
 submissions return accepted=false with "already claimed"
 - Retry until confirmed — phone retries POST every 10 s until DGX returns confirmed=true;
 encrypted key persists in SharedPrefs so retries survive app restart

